<subSubSection id="690AD9D104210F4033D009A9052393D4" pageNumber="810" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="19109E0F827EE1F74298CC9B1ADDBECA" pageNumber="810">
<emphasis id="1528EA02673C60F73395C996EDCB4704" italics="true" pageNumber="810">Note:</emphasis>
Blackwell &amp; al. (in 
<taxonomicName id="D8F6B4661389F12E10D549B01A20A507" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C7582C1B4D5EC11FDB61066DAAFD1799" italics="true" pageNumber="810">Sida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
8: 161. 1979) referred to a specimen in LINN as the &quot;type specimen&quot; but did not distinguish between sheets 315.9, 315.18 and 315.32 (which are not part of a single gathering so Art. 9.15 does not apply). Castroviejo &amp; al. (in 
<emphasis id="FB23D6DDFE3CD53F7A76C7FCDF4CB907" italics="true" pageNumber="810">Anales Jard. Bot. Madrid</emphasis>
43: 477. 1987) discussed these specimens in some detail and concluded that 
<taxonomicName id="3F718C47E9160B798A3BC036CC013F53" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">
<emphasis id="9F3CDFAE81323E7934418547BDF86CD5" italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. sativa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a new species based in part on 
<emphasis id="F14EC8499FC9ABE43FC0BE61DB120759" italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. souda</emphasis>
Loefl. (1758), which Linnaeus cited in the protologue of 
<emphasis id="98D039D8D9AD708473B5E4AF872FE664" italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<taxonomicName id="07B56F0023CFEB361B7D266F7A9E0F54" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">S. sativa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Castroviejo &amp; al. argue that 
<emphasis id="2214500329D9C00740D0CD7D83E9C0CA" italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. souda</emphasis>
is merely an orthographic variant of 
<taxonomicName id="7DE5DC03FF83533A116E7F09C2C38596" authority="L. (1753)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="soda">
<emphasis id="7F067179ECCDD3CA644D9B135B27CFFF" italics="true" pageNumber="810">S. soda</emphasis>
L. (1753)
</taxonomicName>
but that in 1762, Linnaeus recognised that 
<normalizedToken id="4FB743A50DC2838F082633642571B6B3" originalValue="Löfling’s">Loefling's</normalizedToken>
plant was distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="0AF5A66D7B728E3654DA08E962C633F2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Malvaceae" genus="Sida" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malvales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="soda">
<emphasis id="AF4AFABEADCA13089DEBA3A53D420246" italics="true" pageNumber="810">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="75A80F539F591A597C46A0D7EC667926" italics="true" pageNumber="810">soda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and gave it the name 
<emphasis id="0D049C6D099627C1E2DD5DB4E5DF952D" italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<taxonomicName id="B3E92B96BBA2590656A36B650984B459" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1762" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Salsola" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sativa">S. sativa</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In the absence of 
<emphasis id="2347F7D807110209456F2C4DAC273525" italics="true" pageNumber="810">
<normalizedToken id="97E96C84524F62529956850D0D8E14B4" originalValue="Löfling">Loefling</normalizedToken>
123
</emphasis>
, they typified the name using 
<normalizedToken id="8807DF84EFDA02FFC6149A6884A07568" originalValue="Löfling’s">Loefling's</normalizedToken>
description, though this is now contrary to Art. 9, a type being either a specimen or an illustration.
</paragraph>
